<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2005-08-15T23:01:07-07:00</updated>
<published>2005-08-15T23:01:07-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=492&amp;p=3777#p3777</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=492&amp;p=3777#p3777"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Actual NES/FAMICON/FAMICLONE framerate?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=492&amp;p=3777#p3777"><![CDATA[
Yes, the NES video deviates from the NTSC standard. Instead of 262.5 lines per field it has 262 lines, in order to get a progressive image. (At the time the NES came out, there wasn't enough memory to make a decent interlaced image. In fact, the first major console to have "most" games interlaced was the Dreamcast.) It also has 227.333 color clock periods per scanline rather than the expected 227.5. Thus (not counting the differences between even and odd frames) the NES frame rate is 3579545.45 / 227.333 / 262 = about 60.10 FPS instead of the 59.94 that your equipment expects.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon Aug 15, 2005 11:01 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
